I think this is actually a pilot boat, and not a tug (which would be much, much larger and reinforced ;)

In the easiest boat identification I've ever tried to make ;)  this is the Pilot boat <i>JOHNSON.</i> That's because &quot;Since 1906 all of the pilot boats up to the present day (2001) have been named Johnson, either from the Capt. I W Johnson family or Capt W. H. Johnson family.&quot;[<a href="http://books.google.com/books?id=6Ybysl1iMVsC&amp;pg=PA11&amp;lpg=PA11&amp;dq=pilot+boat,+Boca+Grande,+Florida&amp;source=bl&amp;ots=jWsYAzKKXc&amp;sig=sgc8ysIkdgEN_XMjUA83yLlv45E&amp;hl=en&amp;sa=X&amp;ei=R9GsUdGHEJe34APi94CQDQ&amp;ved=0CGoQ6AEwCQ#v=onepage&amp;q=pilot boat, Boca Grande, Florida&amp;f=false" rel="nofollow">1</a>] The famous harbor pilot family stretched from 1888 through 2001. [<a href="http://bocabeacon.com/news/featured-news/4309-the-johnson-boys-and-local-harbor-pilot-history-featured-at-history-bytes" rel="nofollow">2</a>]
&nbsp;

Arrrgh -- so much for &quot;easy boat identifications!&quot;  I just reread the reference source, and it <u>doesn't</u> say all the pilot boats were named Johnson.  What it says is &quot;Since 1906 all of the Boca Grande pilots up to the present day have been named Johnson...&quot;

This certainly proves the adage &quot;you get what you look for&quot; -- I was looking for pilot <u>boats</u>, and pilot boats I found ;(    
